This was found while moving to c++20 by an anonymous internal contributor. Integrating the finding to mainline.

std::unique iterates on elements of the container, and removes all but the first element matching the predicate, but does not resize the container. This means the following code doesn't assert.

```cpp
    std::vector<int> v = { 1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3 };
    assert(v.size() == 6);
    std::unique(v.begin(), v.end());
    assert(v.size() == 6);
```

The function returns a past-end iterator, and all the undefined elements are at the end of the container, meaning we can safely erase them, and fix the container size.

Signed-off-by: Nathan Gauër <brioche@google.com>

